{
  "text": "Inflammation may play a role in the etiology of lung cancer [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Individuals with tuberculosis, HIV infection, or chronic lung infection with Chlamydia pneumoniae seem to have an excess risk of lung cancer independent of tobacco use [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Environmental agents associated with elevated lung cancer risk, such as silica or asbestos, may damage the lung by inducing chronic inflammation. Lung cancer risk is elevated in individuals with emphysema [CITATION_7] , interstitial lung disease [CITATION_8] , and asthma [CITATION_9] , which could similarly reflect effects of the underlying inflammatory disorders. Conversely, use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs has been associated with decreased lung cancer risk [CITATION_10] .",
